        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Fire Alarm Installation in Aurora, CO: What Commercial Property Owners Need to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">If you own or manage commercial property in Aurora, Colorado, your fire alarm system requirements are governed by a layered framework: NFPA 72 at the national level, the Colorado Fire Code at the state level, and Aurora Fire Rescue at the local enforcement level. Getting this right matters — Aurora Fire Rescue's Fire Prevention Division enforces fire alarm requirements aggressively, and the penalty for an inoperable or uncertified fire alarm system isn't just a fine. It's a mandatory fire watch that costs more per day than a full system installation. Here's exactly what Aurora requires, what systems cost, and how to stay compliant.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">Aurora Fire Alarm Requirements: The Legal Framework</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The City of Aurora adopts the International Fire Code (IFC) with local and Colorado-specific amendments. The Colorado Fire Code, enforced by Aurora Fire Rescue, references NFPA 72: National Fire Alarm and Signaling Code as the governing standard for fire alarm system design, installation, testing, and maintenance. No fire alarm system may be installed, modified, or placed into service in Aurora without a permit from the Aurora Building Division and subsequent inspection and approval by Aurora Fire Rescue.</p>

        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Colorado adds meaningful layers on top of the base IFC. The state adopted the 2015 International Fire Code with Colorado amendments, and those amendments include enhanced requirements for high-altitude installations (Aurora sits at approximately 5,500 feet above sea level), specific monitoring requirements for remote facilities, and additional provisions for wildland-urban interface (WUI) zones that affect parts of eastern Aurora and the Aurora Hills area.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">When Is a Fire Alarm System Required in Aurora?</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Not every commercial building in Aurora requires a monitored fire alarm system, but the threshold is lower than most building owners assume. Under the Colorado Fire Code and NFPA 72, fire alarm systems are required in:</p>

        <div class="flex flex-col gap-3 mb-6">
          {[
            'Assembly occupancies (Group A): Restaurants, bars, theaters, arenas, places of worship with occupant loads over 300. Aurora\'s extensive restaurant and entertainment corridor along East Colfax and Havana Street triggers these requirements for most venues.',
            'Educational occupancies (Group E): Schools, daycare centers, and any facility with over 100 occupants under age 18. Aurora has numerous school campuses and early childhood centers subject to these requirements.',
