        </div>

        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Even buildings not explicitly required to have a fire alarm system may need one when applying for a certificate of occupancy for certain use changes, after significant renovation, or when the building's occupant load increases. When in doubt, pull the permit and get Aurora Fire Rescue's plan review sign-off before starting any alarm work.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">NFPA 72: The Technical Standard Behind Every Aurora Fire Alarm</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">NFPA 72 (National Fire Alarm and Signaling Code) is the technical backbone of every fire alarm installation in Aurora. The 2019 edition is the currently adopted version in Colorado. Understanding its key requirements helps building owners evaluate system proposals and understand why certain components are specified.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">System Initiating Devices</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">NFPA 72 governs placement requirements for all initiating devices. Smoke detectors must be installed within 21 feet on center along the ceiling (reduced to 18 feet in corridors). Heat detectors use spacing tables based on the detector's listed spacing rating and ceiling height. Pull stations must be within 5 feet of each exit door, with maximum 200-foot travel distances between pull stations throughout the building. For properties in Aurora's newer commercial developments along the E-470 and I-225 corridors, these requirements apply during initial construction — and retrofitting them into existing tenant improvements is where costs escalate quickly.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Notification Appliances</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">NFPA 72 Chapter 18 governs audible and visible notification appliances. Audible devices must produce a minimum 15 dB above the average ambient sound level, never less than 75 dB at the pillow for sleeping areas. In Aurora's industrial parks and warehouse facilities near Fitzsimons and the airport, ambient noise levels often require higher-output horn/strobes. Visible (strobe) notification is required in areas where ambient noise exceeds 105 dB and in all areas accessible to hearing-impaired occupants under the Americans with Disabilities Act — which applies to virtually every public-facing commercial space.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Monitoring Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">NFPA 72 Chapter 26 requires that fire alarm systems transmit signals to a listed central station, remote supervising station, or proprietary supervising station. In plain language: your fire alarm must be monitored 24/7 by a UL-listed central station. Monitoring must be capable of notifying Aurora Fire Communications within 90 seconds of receiving an alarm signal. Self-monitoring or local-only alarms do not meet this requirement for commercial occupancies. Aurora Fire Rescue verifies active monitoring during inspections and accepts no substitutes for properly listed central station monitoring.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Addressable vs. Conventional Systems in Aurora</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Conventional fire alarm systems divide a building into circuits (zones), telling you which zone triggered but not which device. Addressable systems assign a unique address to every device — every detector, pull station, and module. When an alarm triggers, the panel (and Aurora Fire Rescue dispatch) knows the exact location of the triggering device, not just the zone.</p>

        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">For buildings over 10,000 square feet, multiple floors, or complex floor plans, Colorado fire marshals and Aurora Fire Rescue strongly prefer — and in many occupancy types effectively require — addressable systems. The reason is response efficiency: when a fire alarm activates at 2 AM in a 200,000 square foot warehouse near DIA, knowing the exact device location vs. "somewhere in zone 4" matters enormously for emergency response. Addressable systems cost 15–25% more upfront, but the operational benefits (faster troubleshooting, no nuisance alarm chasing, easier expansion) justify the premium for virtually any commercial installation.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">Fire Alarm Installation Costs in Aurora, CO</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-3">Installation costs in the Denver-Aurora metro area reflect both the labor market (competitive but not inexpensive) and the Colorado-specific requirements that add complexity vs. other markets:</p>

